Package com.nbkelly

Class Drafter

java.lang.Object
com.nbkelly.Drafter
Direct Known Subclasses:
MakeHelper, SampleClass
public abstract class Drafter
extends Object
The Drafter class serves as the base of the 'Drafter' drafting tool.

this class is not meant to be directly inherited, but rather a subclass and set of auxiliary files are generated using drafter.sh or easy.sh

Main Pipeline:
1) setCommands(): set the commands this program depends upon.
2) actOnCommands(): pre-process all the commands as needed.
3) doSolveProblem(): solve whatever problem you need to solve.

    Drafter()

    • actOnCommands

      protected abstract void actOnCommands()
      Post-process commands.

      In the execution pipeline, this occurs after the user commands have validated, but before the solveProblem command begins. Use this section to sanity check your inputs and variables, to assert that files exist, etc.

    • setCommands

      protected abstract Command[] setCommands()
      Construct a set of command-arguments that the user must enter to run the program.

      In the execution pipeline, this occurs before commands are validated and before the solveProblem command begins. Use this section to define the parameters of the problem in terms of what the user interacts with. See the *Command classes for more details.

      Returns:
      an array of commands representing what the user must interact with

    • solveProblem

      protected abstract int solveProblem() throws Exception
      Perform the necessary steps to solve your problem.

      In the execution pipeline, this occurs after commands are specified and validated. Use this section to perform the main computations necessary to run your program.

      Returns:
      an integer return code marking the exit status of your program. 0 = success, anything else marks failure.
      Throws:
      Exception

    • run

      protected void run​(String[] argv)
      Runs the given program.

      More specifically, we:
      1) Set all default commands
      2) *Add any additional user-based commands 3) Process all commands 4) Act based on the results of the default commands 5) *Act on the results of all user-input commands 6) Perform any pre-processing on the input 7) *Run the 'solveProblem' function. This is the actual user code.

      Parameters:
      argv - the argument vector for the program
      Since:
      1.0
